[1] Avian influenza Report week 4
Date: 27 Jan 2015
Source: CHP (Reporting period: 18 Jan 2015-24 Jan 2015 (week 4) [edited]
http://www.chp.gov.hk/files/pdf/2015_avian_influenza_report_vol11_wk04.pdf


Avian influenza report week 4 [11(4)]
------------------------------
1. There were no new human cases of avian influenza A(H5N1) reported by the World Health Organization (WHO).*

2. From 2010 to 2014, 32 to 62 confirmed human cases of avian influenza A(H5N1) were reported to WHO annually (according to onset date). In 2015 (as of 24 Jan 2015), there were no new cases so far.**

3. During this reporting period, one confirmed human case of avian influenza A(H7N9) in Hong Kong was reported by the Centre for Health Protection (CHP) of the Department of Health. This imported case is the 2nd case in Hong Kong this winter [2014-15] and the 12th case in Hong Kong. In addition, 11 human cases of avian influenza A(H7N9) (Guangdong (9), Shanghai (1) and Zhejiang (1)) were reported by the Health and Family Planning Commission of Guangdong Province and other Mainland health authorities, while one human case of avian influenza A(H7N9) from British Columbia Province was reported by the Public Health Agency of Canada. Since March 2013 (as of 26 Jan 2015), there were a total of 513 cases reported.

* Since 21 Nov 2012, WHO only publishes information on human cases with avian influenza A(H5N1) infection on a monthly basis in "Influenza at human-animal interface: Monthly Risk Assessment Summary." Cases of human infection with H5N1 will only be reported in Disease Outbreak News for events that are unusual or associated with potential increased risks.

** According to date of disease onset

This week's highlights [as of 26 Jan 2015; Sources: WHO, National Health and Family Planning Commission (NHFPC), Mainland health authorities, Public Health Agency of Canada, CHP and World Organisation for Animal Health (OIE)] may be seen in Table 1-9 at the URL cited above.

Avian Influenza Report is a weekly report produced by the Respiratory Disease Office, Centre for Health Protection of the Department of Health. This report highlights global avian influenza activity in humans and birds.

