[This is the 5th day in a row that Guangdong province is reporting avian influenza cases. Little is coming out of other provinces either because of lack of cases or failure to report.

A map of Shenzhen can be accessed at http://www.maplandia.com/china/new-territories/shenzhen/.
A map of Meizhou City can be accessed at http://www.maplandia.com/china/guangdong/mei-xian/meizhou/. - Mod.LK]

******
[3] China: Case update H7N9
Date: Tues 27 Jan 2015
Source: VDU's Blog [edited]
http://virologydownunder.blogspot.com.au/2014/11/influenza-ah7n9-virus-detection-numbers.html


See map of influenza A(H7N9) case detection, numbers and graphs, with likely province of acquisition, updated 27 Jan 2015 by Ian Mackay. The numbers are gathered from Ministries of Health for the provinces and municipalities of China, the World Health Organization and FluTrackers. The case numbers presented publicly, and used in these graphs, are expected to represent only a fraction of all the cases that have and are occurring.

Dr. Mackay also writes on the need for societal change in his blog http://virologydownunder.blogspot.com.au/2015/01/societal-change-and-h7n9.html.

The importance of societal change for controlling infectious disease outbreaks really cannot be overstated. For Ebola virus disease, it came down to stopping the tradition of direct contact with the bodies of those who have died and direct contact in general. For MERS, it seems that occasional camel contact triggers insertion of the MERS-CoV virus into hospitals, where lax infection prevention and control practices add to the case load.

For influenza A(H7N9) virus cases, it is the habit of obtaining live poultry from retail markets, where rare, virus-laden [chickens] are culled and handed over because of a desire to see, choose, and purchase the tastiest fresh chicken. There is a common thread among these stories about direct contact or inefficient droplet-transmitting virus infections: we can stop their spread. ... - more

